They contain, not only vitals on the decedent, but also information on the parents and where the deceased was buried. Of course, the validity of the information is only as good as the informant. Many times the informant is the spouse or a relative of the deceased, but all the information must be checked against other sources. Like all the other death books that I have written, I have included several indexes that should help you in your research. First, each deceased person has four pages with all of their information. Make sure you look at the first page for the deceased. The first page includes: • Deceased’s Name • Date & Place of Death • Date & Place of Birth • Vital Statistics (Gender-Race-Marital Status) At the end of the book is a index alphabetised by dad, then mom and followed by informant and finally the spouse. I have also listed the age of the spouse, if listed. There are going to be errors. Some of these names are barely legible. I tried my best to decipher all the information, but I am sure I missed a few. Feel free to email me at octkin@amail.com for corrections.
